An unprecedented future
JERUSALEM – With my now nearly 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present were foreseen by anyone.
Experts examined the past, but due to their entrapment in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, in which, given a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, even more events are interdependent, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation that cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and their leaders is diminishing. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are borderless.
Global companies want to conduct their business all over the world, which on the one hand undermines sovereignty, but on the other hand weakens racism, prejudices, and nationalism to a significant extent.
As a result of this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. It is more technologically adept than its parents and connected through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently being led is unsuitable for the new times.
But there are political "free-riders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. Not, however, through the further development of an agenda of freedom, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, mainly Islamist extremists appropriate the protests of the younger generation for themselves, thereby stealing their revolution.
Israel has responded positively to the will of the younger generation, yet it should not and cannot interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are at heart with the rebellious youth and their legitimate longing for freedom and fundamental rights, which should enable them to be heard, to choose their political leadership, and to earn their living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, for the existence as an island of prosperity amidst a sea of poverty is unnatural.
Yet there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists are trying to gain control over less well-organized liberals in elections and thereby prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the region's fundamental problems.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way toward freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example to others in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, for its success is grounded in the fact that the country had absolutely nothing at the beginning.
Upon our return to our homeland, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. As a result, we today have the highest per capita percentage of scientists and patents.
Approximately 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and yet achieve higher crop yields per square meter of cultivated area than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also create.
We are gladly ready to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything within our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to dominate another people, and that is not Israel's destiny.
We are sincerely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who seek to manipulate civil movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and groundbreaking political measures against the extremists must be taken.
Iran, in particular, is a source of moral decay, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. Legitimate protests by its own citizens are crushed, and efforts are made against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Moreover, Iran uses several proxies to incite terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, the country's leaders could shake the Near and Middle East and further incite extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to call for the destruction of Israel.
But Israel is not the only one threatened. Iran is a danger to peace and stability throughout the world.
The democracies of this world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it becomes impossible.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to engage with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to realize their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children to be creative and innovative.
Self-actualization is as important as free expression.
I write this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overrated and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
